<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / International Company News: Reduced interest charge behind
rise at British Data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Data Management, the data storage specialist which came to the
market through a placing a year ago, reported doubled pre-tax profits of
Pounds 1.66m for the six months ended December 31, against Pounds 779,000
last time.
Sales rose 13 per cent from Pounds 6.2m to Pounds 7.04m. The pre-tax figure
was struck after a much reduced interest charge - down from Pounds 687,000
to Pounds 53,000.
Earnings per share rose 25 per cent to 6.5p and the group declared an
interim dividend of 1.5p. The directors said the earnings figure was
flattered by a Pounds 138,000 tax charge that was significantly lower due to
Pounds 258,000 of over-provisioning in the previous year.
Mr Stephen Crown, British Data's chairman, said a strict comparison of
earnings could not be made because in the previous year BDM paid no tax
because of losses brought forward.
He said he continued to seek substantial organic growth that would be
supplemented by bolt-on acquisitions.
The company expected to gain a significant amount of new work from the
government which, through its market testing programme, is seeking to farm
out support functions.
</TEXT>
