<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
According to World In Action (8.30 ITV) food poisoning in Britain is out of
control. Four years after the salmonella row, instances of food poisoning
have risen by a third. Yet this report claims that plans for compulsory
hygiene training for food handlers have been quietly dropped, various
products providing ideal breeding conditions for bugs have been exempted
from temperature controls, and ministers now want to dismantle some consumer
protection laws altogether. In the first of three programmes called Roots
Schmoots (9.00 C4), the wise-cracking novelist Howard Jacobson sets off for
Israel to find out what it means to have Jewish roots. We are told that the
three-part psychological thriller A Statement of Affairs (9.00 and 10.40
ITV) is about six reasonably contented 30-something people who eat, drink,
play badminton and go for long rambles along the seashore 'never suspecting
that their cosy world is about to fall apart'. In Panorama (9.30 BBC1), Jane
Corbin reports on Iran's efforts to acquire weapons of mass destruction:
biological, chemical and even nuclear.
