<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / Overheated debate of economic niceties produces trade in
insults: The argument which has split the Treasury's panel of seven wise men
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A THICK cloud of recrimination, hurt pride and embarrassment has settled
over the UK economics profession after the angry blast by Prof Tim Congdon
directed at the other six members of the government's new panel of economic
advisers.
Prof Congdon says in an open letter to the six, to be published this week,
that he has been 'dismayed' by the work of the group - set up only three
months ago - on the grounds of what he says is his fellow members' lack of
understanding of the basics of economics.
The substance of Prof Congdon's accusations - that the other members of the
panel, with much of the economics establishment, do not account adequately
for the money supply in their economic analysis - does not surprise those
who know him. Prof Congdon, a staunch monetarist who is economic adviser at
Gerrard &amp; National, the City discount house, feels passionately about his
subject. He combines a high regard for his own intellectual capabilities
with a fondness for lecturing his fellow economists.
These traits have won Prof Congdon respect but have also brought him a fair
number of detractors. 'He's an arrogant so-and-so,' was one of the comments
from members of the economics community at the weekend.
In the professor's favour is that his forecasting record since the mid-1980s
has been significantly better than that of many other economists. He
correctly foresaw both the inflationary boom of 1986-88 and the seriousness
and length of the recession which followed soon afterwards.
In terms of forecasting he has performed far better than the teams of
economists at the UK's two biggest and best-known academic establishments in
the discipline - the National Institute of Economic and Social Research and
the London Business School.
They are represented on the Treasury panel by the institute's director, Mr
Andrew Britton, and the LBS's head of forecasting, Prof David Currie.
Prof Congdon is also a member of the generally respected Liverpool Six group
of monetarist economists, which correctly argued from early 1991 that the
recessionary forces in Britain would ultimately compel the country to leave
the European exchange rate mechanism.
What has surprised many about Prof Congdon's latest tirade - which he showed
to the FT on Friday - is the force of the invective in his 12-page letter
and the fact that he included in his sweeping criticisms his fellow
monetarist, Prof Patrick Minford of Liverpool University - who is another
member of the Treasury panel.
The letter demonstrates not only Prof Congdon's lack of regard for restraint
in conducting economic arguments, but the gulf between him and Prof Minford
 -another member of the Liverpool Six - when it comes to considering the
technical role of money in the economy.
In his letter, to be published in Gerrard &amp; National's monthly economic
review, Prof Congdon criticises the Liverpool academic on the detailed
points of monetarism and concludes that he has no 'means of analysing the
effects on the economy of a change in the quantity of money'.
Prof Minford retorted at the weekend that Prof Congdon was 'plain wrong' and
'ignorant'. He added: 'The whole thing is embarrassing and a bit pathetic. I
am afraid Prof Congdon does not understand modern economics and doesn't
listen to other people's views.
Prof Gordon Pepper, of the City University Business School, a further member
of the Liverpool Six, said Prof Congdon's letter was 'incredibly
irritating'.
Prof Pepper said: 'For him to attack the neo-Keynsian economics
establishment in the UK and its lack of success in economic analysis is fair
enough. But going about this in this rude way, and by including Prof Minford
in his sweeping comments, undermines his case.'
Two of the other members of the panel - Mr Andrew Sentance of the
Confederation of British Industry and Prof Wynne Godley of Cambridge
University - both expressed their displeasure at Prof Congdon's remarks. Mr
Britton - who is a particular target of Prof Congdon's cutting comments -
said he did not want to comment until he had read the full text of the
letter. 'I might not want to comment then either,' he added.
Yesterday Prof Congdon found at least one wholehearted ally among the other
ranks of monetarist economists. Mr Paul Turnbull, chief UK economist at
stockbrokers Smith New Court and a former colleague of Prof Congdon, said:
'In my view the vast majority of UK economists do not place enough emphasis
on money and credit, an oversight which has led to dramatic failures in
forecasting by mainstream economists in recent years. I sympathise entirely
with Prof Congdon's views.'
</TEXT>
