<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / CBI expects pay rises below 2.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIT LABOUR costs in British manufacturing industry are expected to continue
falling over the next few months, the Confederation of British Industry
says.
It expects productivity to increase by up to 4 per cent and pay settlements
to fall below 2.5 per cent.
Figures from the CBI pay databank for the three months to the end of January
show average manufacturing pay settlements at 2.5 per cent and
service-sector settlements averaging 2.8 per cent.
It is the first time that the databank, which covers more than 1,400
companies, has recorded settlements below 3 per cent across the whole
economy.
The CBI also notes that one in three companies, in both manufacturing and
the service sector, has introduced a pay freeze of up to one year since last
August.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the CBI, said: 'What matters now is
that we keep up the progress. If we can do that we will be better placed
than when we came out of the last recession to avoid inflation and to seize
competitive advantages in the marketplace.'
The Engineering Employers Federation recently recorded similar figures for
settlements and pay freezes.
However, Industrial Relations Services, the independent pay analyst,
recorded slightly higher average pay settlements for the quarter to the end
of January of 3.1 per cent, and recorded pay freezes covering a fifth of
settlements.
The continuing uncertainty about the medium-term movement of pay settlements
and average earnings is, however, underlined by the pay assumptions of the
government actuary built into the latest report on benefit up-rating.
Government economists have assumed a very wide range for the increase in
average earnings for 1993-94 with an increase of 3 per cent at the bottom
end and 7 per cent at the top end.
</TEXT>
