<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / Small businesses hope for green light against red tape: An
issue that is seen as more important than the weight of the tax burden -
Spring Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SMALL manufacturing companies' investment scheme, an improved Business
Expansion Scheme and an increase in the funds available for the Loan
Guarantee Scheme are the sort of measures that business lobbyists would like
to see in the Budget on March 16 to help small businesses recover from the
recession.
All three measures were introduced last time British industry was struggling
out of a recession. In the Budget presented by Sir Geoffrey Howe in March
1983 they formed part of what the FT called 'probably a record number of new
measures' to help small businesses.
Ten years on little appears to have changed. The small-business lobbyists
are pressing hard for something to replace the BES - which is due to expire
at the end of this year - and for a revitalisation of the Loan Guarantee
Scheme to make it more attractive to the banks and more affordable to
business.
Manufacturing businesses do not rank a specific mention in this year's
Budget submissions but they would derive the most benefit if the chancellor
responded to pleas for a more generous regime of first-year investment
allowances. In 1983 engineering was considered an important enough element
of the manufacturing sector to rank for special treatment.
Hopes that something will be done for the makers of goods rather than the
providers of services received a boost on Thursday with the strong
endorsement given to the manufacturing sector by Mr John Major.
Exporters may also have taken encouragement from the prime minister's
evident wish to promote exports. Last week, shortly after returing from a
successful trade mission to Saudi Arabia, Mr Major offered to take more
businessmen with him on foreign trips if it helped to open doors. More
generous government support for export credit insurance is one item on the
lobbyists' shopping list.
Mr Major also gave a broad hint in the Commons that small businesses would
be among the main beneficiaries of any tax concessions.
A study of ministerial speeches in the weeks leading up to the Budget is
probably not the most effective way of divining the chancellor's intentions.
The Treasury's purdah rules are unlikely to permit even the prime minister
to signal the government's intentions in any detail.
But inevitably the business lobbyists are attempting to read the runes of
government policy as best they can. They are trying to sketch in those
elements of their detailed Budget presentations which are most likely to
survive the Treasury's red pencil.
The constraints imposed by a ballooning public sector borrowing requirement
will put a brake on the more costly measures which the small-business
lobbyists have been seeking - such as cuts in the uniform business rate.
Calls for a reduction in capital gains tax, which at parity with top-rate
income tax is seen as a brake on enterprise, may also go unheeded. Mr Ian
Peters, deputy director of smaller-companies policy at the CBI, said: 'The
key is that they will be looking for issues which don't cost very much.'
This squeeze on government revenues could persuade the chancellor to take
the low-cost route to pleasing small businesses by cutting red tape.
Administering the tax and social security system represents a considerable
burden on businesses in terms of management time.
Only last month the government announced a wide-ranging review of the
bureaucratic burden on business, but it could take early action in the
Budget to simplify the present tax system. Mr Richard Brown, policy director
at the British Chambers of Commerce, said merging tax and national insurance
would provide relief for small companies.
The complexities of the VAT system and the harshness of the penalties
imposed for errors have again featured prominently in the small-business
lobbyists' submissions this year. The serious misdeclaration penalty,
applied indiscriminately for simple mistakes or deliberate fraud, is still
under review - after being cut from 20 per cent to 15 per cent last year -
and a further easing is hoped for.
The Federation of Small Businesses has suggested the elimination of VAT on
transactions between VAT-registered businesses. This would cut
administration costs, minimise the problem of bad debts and reduce the risk
of incurring penalties without affecting the VAT yield to the Treasury. VAT
is, after all, meant to be a tax on final consumption, not on business, the
lobbyists say.
Apparently minor adjustments to VAT administration can have quite
significant benefits for small companies. Immediate relief from charging VAT
on bad debts would help small businesses, given the present high rates of
business failure. At present businesses can claim relief only after one
year. Raising the VAT threshold from Pounds 36,600 could take businesses out
of the VAT net, but a rise above the rate of inflation would need to be
cleared with Brussels.
In spite of the similarity between the small-companies' Budget submissions
of 1993 and 1983, much has changed in the intervening decade. The important
role played by small businesses in creating jobs, broadening consumer choice
and stimulating innovation is now more widely recognised.
But this has not prevented governments from devising tax and social security
systems of excessive complexity. The annual Budget round gives the
small-business lobbyist the chance to remind civil servants that simplicity
and ease of implementation are, if anything, more important than the weight
of the burden imposed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
