FT  08 MAR 93 / 53,000 council jobs 'lost last year'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 53,000 local government jobs were lost last year, statistics prepared
by the Local Authority Joint Staffing Watch show.
Moves to save jobs this year, such as the deal between unions and Sheffield
City Council, where unions traded a pay cut for jobs, are likely to be
limited because most councils have set their budgets and made their plans
for 1993-94.
But the labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities said
yesterday that more councils and unions might move in that direction in
1993-94.
In Sheffield nearly 20,000 employees voted to take a pay cut in exchange for
shorter working hours to stop the city council making 1,400 of them
redundant.
According to the Local Authority Joint Staffing Watch's statistics more than
31,000 jobs were lost to local authorities in 1991 and 39,000 last year. In
1989 there was no real change.
It is understood that a greater percentage of last year's job losses were
white-collar than in the past.
Mr Stephen Bubb, secretary of the AMA, said that last year's job losses
confirmed his worst fears. 'We believe that up to 100,000 more local
government jobs will be lost in the next 18 months,' he said.
Most councils have now set their budgets and made plans for redundancies
based on the government's desired 1.5 per cent pay ceiling for public sector
workers.
The Local Government Management Board, the employers' organisation, said it
did not believe that Sheffield would set a precedent. 'There were unique
circumstances in Sheffield,' it said.
It is understood that a majority of councils have had informal talks with
unions over pay freezes, but no agreements have been reached.
According to the Local Government Chronicle the 1.5 per cent pay limit is
forcing councils to renegotiate contracts with employees who have
index-linked pay.
A number of councils, including Bracknell Forest Borough Council, introduced
index linked pay for some groups of workers affected by compulsory
competitive tendering.
