<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / Need a quality certificate? Ask Tom, Dick or Harry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH companies are paying thousands of pounds and spending hours of
management time to qualify for a quality standard which appears to have a
quality control problem of its own.
The BS5750 quality standard has already been obtained by about 17,000
companies. But it has now emerged that a loophole in the rules means anyone
can award a BS5750, which certifies that a company's internal procedures are
properly organised.
Consultancies and other organisations which issue and monitor BS5750
certificates are not required to register with the National Accreditation
Council for Certification Bodies (NACCB), an industry body which ultimately
answers to the Department of Trade and Industry.
'There appears to be absolutely no control over the organisations making the
award,' said Mr Stephen Halliday, principal lecturer in small business at
Buckinghamshire College of Higher Education. 'The government must take steps
to ensure that BS5750 can be awarded only by reputable, accredited
organisations.'
Two dozen organisations have been accredited but the NACCB estimates that up
to a dozen which have not registered are actively issuing certificates. Even
those wanting to register have to operate for between one and two years
without formal accreditation while the NACCB assesses their performance.
The NACCB said it thought buyers were sophisticated enough not to be taken
in by suppliers sporting certificates issued by 'cowboys.' But the British
Standards Institution, which is accredited and which has issued most BS5750
certificates, said it was concerned at this loophole. There is intense
commercial competition between the BSI and other certification
organisations, not least on price.
The discovery that anyone can offer the BS5750 will add to the controversy
surrounding the certificate. Some small businesses, which are increasingly
being required by large customers to obtain the certificate, complain that
its procedures are costly and unduly bureaucratic.
Most companies must pay a minimum of several thousand pounds in consultants'
and registration fees to prove they meet BS5750 requirements, and up to
Pounds 2,000 each year to show they still comply. Smaller companies,
especially, also find the process a significant burden on senior management
time.
Mr Paul Hewlett, secretary of the NACCB, said: 'The professional buyers are
pretty well educated to ask if their suppliers have been certified by an
accredited organisation. There is not much of a market for the cowboys.'
Only accredited certification organisations are allowed to put the NACCB
logo, consisting of a tick and crown, alongside the BS5750 logo, Mr Hewlett
said. But business organisations are concerned that many smaller companies
may not be aware of this distinction or that they have obtained BS5750 from
an unaccredited organisation.
The British Standards Institution said it had urged the government to impose
tighter controls and to give the NACCB greater powers but no action had been
taken.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P99   Nonclassifiable Establishments.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Standards.
</TP>
