<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 93 / Major faces setback in Maastricht vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was last night bracing itself for the possibility of an
embarrassing House of Commons defeat over Maastricht despite Mr John Major's
public plea to Tory Euro-sceptics to end their rebellion against the treaty.
A defeat in the vote by MPs tonight on a minor amendment proposed by Labour
would not wreck ratification of the treaty. But it would undermine seriously
the prime minister's efforts to re-assert the government's authority at
Westminster.
Speaking at the Conservative spring conference in Harrogate on Saturday, Mr
Major told party activists that the party could no longer afford the
'luxury' of disunity. That view was echoed in warnings from colleagues that
important parts of the government's legislative programme were being
derailed by the row over Europe. The general atmosphere of uncertainty in
the highest ranks of the government was underlined by renewed weekend
speculation about a July cabinet reshuffle.
Sir Norman Fowler, Tory party chairman, rejected suggestions that he wanted
to return to the cabinet this year as chancellor or home secretary. He has
told Mr Major that he expects to stay at Conservative central office at
least until next year.
But Mr Norman Lamont's concern at the threat to his position as chancellor
from other senior colleagues was underlined by evidence that he is seeking
to improve his recent frosty relations with much of the media.
With some senior Conservatives suggesting Mr Major should appoint a new
chancellor in a limited July reshuffle, Mr Lamont has set up a series of
high-level meetings with newspaper editors after his March 16 Budget.
The chancellor's hope is that a favourable response to the Budget measures
will strengthen his case for remaining at the Treasury until a more
wide-ranging reshuffle pencilled in by Mr Major for mid-1994.
Last night, the Tory Euro- sceptics were unmoved by Mr Major's warning that
failure to ratify Maastricht would leave Britain 'irrelevant' in Europe.
They signalled they intended to vote tonight for a Labour amendment to the
legislation.
The amendment, which would ensure that British representatives on the
Community's new committee of the regions were elected rather than appointed,
would not itself affect the treaty.
But it would allow the Tory rebels and opposition parties to further prolong
debate by introducing a so-called 'report stage' into the legislation's
passage through the Commons. That would allow the rebels more time to press
their case for a referendum on the treaty and would further disrupt the
government's other legislation.
Ministers were insisting that a defeat might yet be avoided. Tory business
managers will today discuss the possibility of conceding the substance of
the Labour amendment ahead of a vote in the hope of winning the support of
the Liberal Democrats and other small opposition parties.
In an attempt to increase the pressure on the Tory rebels, ministers said
yesterday that new laws to enforce tougher penalties on young offenders and
to reform Sunday trading hours were among those facing delay because so much
time at Westminster was being taken up by Maastricht.
Tories still dogged by tensions Page 7
Heseltine warns miners over pit disruption Page 7
The bogeyman will be back Page 30
</TEXT>
