<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Travel: The river roads of the rainforest - Boats are best
when exploring parts of Malaysia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL J WOODS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ANCIENT outboard motor revved loudly, thrashing at the surface of the
turbulent water so that the long boat quickly lost way against the immutable
force of the current. With great calm the steersman brought the stern almost
against the steep bank where the water was dark and deep and the vegetation
hung over the channel.
Ducking to avoid thick leaves and branches, he dipped the propeller into the
river and turned on the power. Once more we surged forward over a shoal of
stones and into the deeper pool above. Another obstacle had been overcome
and we powered up the River Tembeling through the soaring trees of the
Malaysian rainforest.
The Tembeling is the main route into Malaysia's largest national park, Taman
Nagara, which means, simply, national park. Covering an area of 4,343 square
kilometres of virgin rainforest 130m years old, the park is largely
inaccessible except via rivers. The journey upstream from Kuala Tembeling to
the park headquarters and the new Taman Nagara Resort at Kuala Tahan takes
about three hours depending on the water level.
The long boats thrust powerfully upstream past small riverside settlements
perched on the bank-tops high above the normal river level, for in the
monsoon the river can rise by more than 70 metres, as the line on the wall
at the park headquarters testifies.
I saw a graphic illustration of this rise and fall along one of the
Tembeling's tributaries leading deep into the park. Jammed high above in the
branches of a tree was a trunk probably 10m long and 1m across.
Taman Nagara Resort is incongruous in the remote and wild context of virgin
rainforest. Its rooms, in individual and traditional Malay buildings, are
comfortable, but the city hotel-style restaurant, 24-hour reception and
banqueting hall are incompatible with a jungle setting.
I ate, instead, in the fairy-lit cafes set up on the river beach opposite,
whistling for a boat to carry me across the black swirling waters and
stumbling up the stony beach in the dark. One night I joined a group of
forest guides and national park staff for a celebratory meal, clumsily
balling rice with delicious pieces of river fish and spicy chicken direct
from hand to mouth.
From the park headquarters a variety of trails led into the forest. Some are
short with numbered points of interest, others are longer and take you to
viewpoints or mineral licks. One of them is the route to the highest
mountain on peninsular Malaysia, a seven-day trek. I chose a short route as
a taster and plunged into the trees along a damp, narrow path.
The noise took me completely by surprise - a loud, endlessly repetitive
backing of hums, buzzes, whines, drones and purrs enlivened, now and then,
by rising and falling bells and whoops. It went on constantly, night and
day, a cacophony of insects, frogs, occasional birds and even gibbons.
Somehow this barrage of sound, together with the occasional leech looping
rapidly across the leaves of the forest floor at the slightest sniff of a
meal, produced an atmosphere of malevolence.
The problem with the rainforest is that the action is many floors up in the
penthouse while you are stuck in the dank basement. It is only along the
corridors cut by the rivers and in clearings such as those carved out for
villages and the park headquarters that wildlife becomes apparent.
Early one morning I fruitlessly searched the grounds of the new resort for
some of the 20 bird species which the leaflet told me could commonly be seen
there. I spotted just two, although one was the glorious southern pied
hornbill, its beak adorned with a huge creamy casque. There were also
long-tailed macaque monkeys, raiding the builders' houses for food, and
several species of squirrel.
I spent one night in a hide overlooking a mineral lick. Here half-a-dozen of
us kept vigil armed with powerful torches to flick on at the slightest sound
of a visitor. We were alerted by a noise like munching cornflakes, and there
in the spotlight was a bi-coloured animal, black at front and back with a
broad white belt around its middle, a tapir.
Its early arrival promised well for the rest of the night but it was a
promise not to be fulfilled. Although the tapir came and went several times,
nothing else turned up.
An alternative is to visit the animals themselves, so the next day we
crawled through a grubby cave in search of bats. There were two species, a
large fruit-eating bat and a much smaller insectivorous horseshoe bat. Both
were hanging in great numbers from the grey ceiling and festooning the rocky
walls.
This was no place for the phobic. Along with the bats, a large toad sat
darkly in the stream below while a white cave racer with a brilliant red
tongue, a bat-eating snake, slid silently around the walls, insinuating its
body into cracks and slithering from crevice to crevice.
The Malaysian jungle is home to one of the three species of great ape, the
orang-utan, though I had to fly to the orang-utan rehabilitation centre at
Sepilok, in the state of Sabah, to see these. Here young orangs, orphaned as
infants or taken from the wild as pets, are re-introduced to life in the
rainforest. A number of learning stages sees them wise enough to live freely
in the forest, returning to a feeding area for supplementary rations of
bananas and milk, a diet which is supposed to encourage them to forage for
more interesting food out of sheer boredom. Even when there are no primates
to be seen, Sepilok offers an ideal opportunity to appreciate the beauty and
majesty of the rainforest.
Travel information: Malaysia Tourism Promotion Board, 57 Trafalgar Square,
London WC2N 5DU. Tel: 071-930-7932.
Aix-les-Bains: The author of last week's article was Stephen Court, not as
attributed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>MYZ  Malaysia, Asia.
</CN>
