<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Arts: Titus deconstructed - Jackie Wullschlager reviews a
mind-gripping new work by east German playwright Heiner Muller, directed by
Gunter Kramer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACKIE WULLSCHLAGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIKE SKITTLES, the cultural giants of the former East Germany are tumbling:
first it was Manfred Wekworth, director of Brecht's Berliner Ensemble; now
even writers who seemed to stand against the regime - Heiner Muller, Christa
Wolf - have been implicated as STASI agents. Muller, Germany's foremost
living dramatist, is a fascinating case because from the start he refused to
reject DDR culture wholesale in favour of capitalism.
But while east Germany has mostly embraced western values with open arms, in
the theatre the reverse has happened. Directors trained in the east -
Muller, Katharina Thalbach, Matthias Langhoff - are in huge demand in the
west. And behind them all, the ghost of Brecht, icon of DDR culture, stalks
German stages more insistently than ever. His influence is overwhelming in
the two major post-war dramatic traditions: theatre as political-moral
debate - classics recast as condition-of-Germany plays have been standard
fare since the Wall fell and theatre as pure aestheticism, texts
deconstructed, action deliberately distanced from life.
At extremes, the Berlin Volksbuhne's rubbish-dump Lear typifies the first,
Robert Wilson's surreal Faustus the second. But the best synthesis of the
two traditions I have yet seen is an eye-opening, nerve-bending,
mind-gripping new Titus Andronicus, reworked by Heiner Muller and directed
in Cologne by Gunter Kramer, Germany's high priest of high stylisation.
Titus is Shakespeare's first and most grisly tragedy. Corpses litter the
stage in minutes, limbs are amputated, tongues cut out, human flesh served
to relatives for supper in a revenge war between conquering Romans and
vanquished Goths. Muller sees in it the ethnic cleansing, systemised rape
and guerilla tactics of the Bosnian conflict and the recent war in
Afghanistan.
When the Goths tip black plastic bags of bodies into the pit, they scrawl
'Death to the Romans' in elegant graffiti across the stage. Forced to learn
the victor's language, terrorists chant 'amo amas amat', as they exchange
mocking homosexual caresses. Some lines, Muller says in the programme, he
heard from Russian soldiers in DDR days. Woven into poetry is an ironic
chorus - 'William Shakespeare, my name and your name glow in blood'. Goths
ridicule Roman speeches by repeating them, a second out of time, like
discordant madrigals.
Muller calls his play Anatomy Titus Fall of Rome: A Shakespeare Commentary;
what interests Kramer is its deadly games of alienation and satire. A silent
first act is mimed to the war music of Philip Glass's Ahknaten; Romans, in
white robes, helmets and feathers, ashen faces painted into masks of
exagerated sensuality with fat red lips, eyebrows pink or blue, sockets
blackened, bop up and down against a waist-high ramp and pull faces, poke
tongues, in the fight to be emperor. It is half Punch and Judy, half eerie,
surreal ritual.
In the hunting scene where Lavinia is raped, she runs in and out of a forest
of metal rods bathed in silver-green light which descend from the ceiling
and jangle as she tries to flee: visual and acoustic symbol of her terror.
When her hands are cut off, the negro Aaron, in dark glasses and black
gloves, seizes her frilly white parasol, sticks it between his legs and
spins handstands. Aestheticised horror, the play of black on white, acrobats
jibing at mutilation: in its acute calculation and rhythm, Kramer's
stylisation disturbs more than the worst of blood and gore.
It is given emotional as well as topical life by a cast tuned to every
nuance of Muller's revision and every swing of Kramer's setting. Gerd Kunath
as Titus pits a rigid, heroic propriety against an absurdist commentary on
his own folly and idealism; when he cuts off his hand to save his sons and
has it returned to him with their heads, he throws the useless limb into the
audience with a shrug at once comic and heartbroken. His flexible face and
ever-moving body now browbeaten and sagging, now blank with horror,
sometimes mad, sometimes murderous, Kunath evokes a desperate warmth and
pity.
As Lavinia, Ingrid Andree changes from complacent Roman puppet to passionate
distraught heroine, to sacrificial victim danced upon as a prop. She returns
to life when she writes, as if the effort comes from the core of her being,
the names of her attackers with a stick held between her teeth into the
sand: a moment at once of perfect Shakespearean tenderness and Beckett-like
sad absurdity, and one of many unforgettable scenes in an extraordinary
production.
In rep at the Schauspielhaus, Cologne
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
