<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Finance and the Family: Revenue's stand hits varsity BES
issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INLAND Revenue does not like business expansion scheme companies which
invest in university accommodation. As reported last week, its reaction to
the Johnson Fry companies which bought accommodation for University College,
London, suggests it is getting tougher as the BES nears its scheduled
demise.
The Revenue has interpreted the BES legislation in such a way that tax
relief would be denied, according to Johnson Fry's chairman, Charles Fry.
But this decision is not final and talks continue.
Johnson Fry argues that the decision to make a summer letting, which caused
the problem, was not the responsibility of the BES companies but of UCL, and
that the legislation refers only to matters under the control of the BES
company. It will pay the costs of any legal action, but it is worth noting
that sponsors do not guarantee that BES relief is available - although they
do undertake to act for investors in trying to ensure that it is.
The main lesson of the affair, according to John Spiers of BESt Investment,
is to avoid schemes where money is raised before the Revenue has granted
provisional approval. Whatever the Revenue's final decision, it has
succeeded in cutting back on university BES issues - Ian Pugh of Allenbridge
says three have been cancelled in the past week.
Meanwhile, BES companies proliferate. The following list, provided by
Allenbridge, shows only those with a contracted exit:
Airways III offers a Pounds 1.17 buy-back price after five years for every
Pounds 1 invested now. Buy-back comes from the Airways Housing Association.
A Priori Growth, sponsored by Neill Clerk, will buy repossessions for the
Britannia building society. Non-recourse loans are available for 74p per
Pounds 1 invested after six months, 78.31p after one year, 87.71p after two
years and 98.24p after three. There is no guarantee after 5 years.
Barratt Fixed Growth fund, sponsored by Capital for Companies and
underwritten by Lloyds Bank, has a five-year buy-back of 115p.
BESSA Bristol &amp; West, sponsored by Close Brothers, buys repossessions for
Bristol &amp; West building society. Non-recourse loans of 74p after six months
are available, with a repayment of 105p per share after five years.
BESSA Cambridge, sponsored by Close Brothers and underwritten by Barclays,
will buy accommodation for Newnham College, Cambridge. Six-month loans of
75p, and a five-year buy-back price of 110.6p per Pounds 1, are available.
Bulldog Premium Growth, sponsored by Charterhouse Tilney, will buy
accommodation for Bellway Homes. Non-recourse loans of 75p per Pounds 1 are
available from Barclays. Buy-back after five years is 112p per Pounds 1.
Govett Asset Builder IV will buy housing for Sanctuary Housing. Five-year
buy-back is 115p.
Homeshare, sponsored by National Westminster and Hambros banks, will buy
houses from NatWest. Six-month loans of 74p, and a five-year buy-back of
Pounds 1.08, are available.
Homes for Littlehampton, sponsored by Matrix-Securities, has a 5-year
buy-back of 117p.
House The Homeless V buys accommodation for the Peabody Trust. 5-year
buy-back is 115p.
The Leeds Permanent Flexible Options Growth scheme, the Portman Multiple
Choice Growth scheme and the Second N&amp;P Multiple Choice Growth scheme are
sponsored by Johnson Fry and offer the same deal as A Priori. Portman is
available now, the rest from Tuesday.
