<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Barclays board loses confidence of some institutions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NUMBER of Barclays Bank's big institutional shareholders said yesterday
they planned to tell the board that they were losing confidence in its top
management.
Institutional shareholders contacted by the Financial Times, which hold
roughly 15 per cent of the bank's shares, expressed varying degrees of
discontent following the news of Barclays' Pounds 242m pre-tax loss and the
halving of its final dividend.
Their comments ranged from the view that Mr Andrew Buxton, Barclays'
chairman and chief executive, should resign, to a desire for board changes.
Mr Buxton said after Thursday's announcement of the loss that investors had
expressed their support for the bank's directors, and their business
strategy.
A number of institutions said they would urge the board to appoint a new
chief executive from outside Barclays - a move they believed it would
resist. The bank has said it will take steps to split the roles of chairman
and chief executive.
Barclays' share price rose yesterday after a near 10 per cent fall on
Thursday. Most securities analysts are forecasting a recovery in Barclays'
fortunes.
Despite doubts about the bank's management, some institutional shareholders
said profits were likely to improve following a pick-up in the economy,
declining interest rates and greater internal lending controls. Several said
they had bought more Barclays shares as prices fell after the earnings
announcement.
Others, accounting for about 6 per cent of the bank's shares, said they
intended to tell management not only that Mr Buxton should cease to hold one
of his two posts but also that he should leave the board entirely.
'I think it is in the interests of shareholders to get a new chairman and a
new chief executive. One of the problems with Barclays is that it has had a
power vacuum at the top,' said one shareholder.
The board's appointment of Mr Buxton as both chairman and chief executive
this January despite reservations among some shareholders was criticised.
Shareholders also pointed to the concentration of losses in the construction
and property sectors as evidence that the bank had not exercised prudent
judgment in allowing itself to become highly exposed to a single sector of
the economy. They said they would seek details of the steps taken to tighten
up the bank's risk management.
London stocks, Page 15
Bottom Line, Weekend II
</TEXT>
