<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Russian parliament set to challenge Yeltsin: Showdown will
threaten reform programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON and DMITRY VOLKOV
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE RUSSIAN parliament yesterday set the stage for a showdown with President
Boris Yeltsin over who holds power in Russia in a move which threatens his
reform programme.
The parliament rejected Mr Yeltsin's proposals for a power-sharing deal and
voted to summon an emergency session of Russia's supreme legislature, the
Congress of People's Deputies, next Wednesday, to debate the constitutional
crisis.
The move came amid signs that the congress, which meets only occasionally,
would also seek to cancel a referendum on power-sharing, to which it agreed
in December.
If the congress blocked both options for Mr Yeltsin to cut the bloated
legislature inherited from Soviet days - either through constitutional
change or by referendum - Mr Yeltsin would have little choice but to call a
personal plebiscite seeking the support of the Russian people.
Such a move, without the backing of the congress, would carry little weight
constitutionally. However, Mr Yeltsin has suggested that it would at least
show who the people support. He has even hinted that he would consider
emergency powers if a power-sharing deal did not follow from the plebiscite.
The president's lawyers already appear to be preparing the way for him to
hold the plebiscite: they warned deputies that they would lose their legal
right to any say over the referendum if they reneged on their December vote
to hold one in the first place.
Mr Vladimir Shumeiko, first deputy prime minister, told deputies earlier
that Mr Yeltsin's proposals for a truce over power-sharing were not final:
the issue was whether they wanted an agreement at all. The answer from
parliament was no.
Mr Shumeiko also told the parliament that Mr Yeltsin wanted the referendum
to ask three questions, which touch on the main issues of the day:
Should there be private ownership of land?
Should a new constitution be adopted by a constituent assembly (as opposed
to the existing congress)?
Should the highest branch of legislative power be a two-chamber legislative
assembly?
But, with some regions threatening not to stage a referendum at all, Mr
Yeltsin knows that a vote would be a high-risk gamble. However, he has
virtually no alternative, pending an 11th-hour Russian compromise, to save
the reforms and his credibility.
Apart from asking the parliament to stick to legislative functions, Mr
Yeltsin has proposed that the central bank and the state statistics
committee be transferred from parliamentary to government control.
He also wants an end to tinkering with the existing Soviet-era constitution
until a constituent assembly approves a new constitution. In the meantime he
is seeking the suspension of Article 104 under which congress is 'the
supreme organ of state power'.
Mr Yeltsin also wants to abolish the system of state property funds, which
answer to the legislative branch and are supposed to share the task of
privatisation with the government's privatisation committees.
Russia loses soul to vodka, Weekend I
</TEXT>
