<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: US economy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The rebound in US employment during February seems to confirm the evidence
of a widespread and strong recovery. Recent purchasing managers surveys and
sharp growth in the last quarter of 1992 point in the same direction. But
care is needed in interpreting the figures. A large number of the new jobs
were part-time and concentrated in the retail and construction sectors,
while manufacturing jobs showed only a slight increase. And given that
employment growth was unexpectedly weak at the end of 1992, the seasonal
adjustment of the figures may be faulty.
Consumer confidence has also been falling, which is hardly consistent with
rapidly improving employment prospects. That decline has accelerated since
President Clinton unveiled his deficit reduction plans. Individuals may
already be retrenching in the expectation of tax increases, while the
beneficiaries of his fiscal stimulus have not yet been clearly identified.
Modest growth concentrated on construction, with productivity improvements
providing most of the boost in manufacturing, may reassure the bond market.
Long yields around 6.75 per cent would thus prove sustainable. If growth
falters, they may even fall further. But equities will struggle harder.
Prices have marked time for two years on the expectation of recovery.
Ratings have fallen as earnings have recovered. On estimated 1993 and 1994
profits Wall Street does not look expensive, but neither is it a steal. With
sustained growth elusive, there may be more waiting to come.
</TEXT>
