<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: On the high wire
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is a sign of the times that the London market still wants to go up
despite the bad news from Barclays. The most obvious reason is the
accommodating stance taken by the Bundesbank. That not only raises the
prospect that the UK will also soon be able to cut interest rates again. A
stronger pound, coupled with the realisation that the UK could have the
strongest economic performance in Europe this year, is pulling foreign
buyers into British equities. Still, there are risks in these assumptions.
The market seems to have brushed aside earlier worries on dividend growth.
Barclays cut its payout this week. Results next week from the likes of
Rolls-Royce and Willis Corroon may show it is not alone. Cookson
demonstrated yesterday that the flow of rights issues is not necessarily
over. The market's present level could look stretched if, as has often
happened in the past, London is jumping to conclusions about the Bundesbank.
Yesterday's quarter point cut in German money market rates makes a cut in
the official rates almost inevitable. But the Bundesbank has also indicated
that it will move cautiously, not least because of its fear that the D-Mark
will weaken too much against the dollar. It may now be cutting the salami in
thicker slices, but it is not yet disposed to hack it off in chunks.
That puts Mr Norman Lamont in a quandary. The next Bundesbank council
meeting is on March 18, two days after the Budget. If he is planning to
sweeten any tax increases with a further rate cut, he will have to take a
risk on matching action from the Bundesbank. Otherwise sterling would again
look uncomfortably exposed.
</TEXT>
