<DOCNO>FT931-5276</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DCGAJADAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930306
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Buba rate cut catches bourses
by surprise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE cut by the Bundesbank of the repo rate caught markets by surprise as it
seemed to signal an imminent cut in the Lombard and discount rates, perhaps
at the next council meeting on March 18, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT moved modestly down as some analysts forecast a period of
consolid-ation for the market following recent strength. The DAX index
closed 4.58 lower at 1,682.82, up 1.4 per cent on the week, as turnover rose
slightly to DM6.5bn from DM6.3bn.
With 'Bundesbank watching' entering a new phase as some observers try to
second-guess when the Lombard and discount rates will actually be cut, other
observers continue to warn that the fundamentals of the German economy
remain weak and are expected to weaken throughout 1993. On this basis, they
say, the present market valuation looks rather stretched and vulnerable to a
downward correction.
One analyst in London commented that many investors still have not fully
appreciated that 1993 earnings are likely to be further downgraded, given
the recent batch of disappointing economic data.
This will be underlined when chemicals report next week. Mr Patrick Shields
of NatWest Securities forecasts a decline in 1992 pre-tax earnings of 47 per
cent for Basf, 26 per cent for Hoechst and 15 per cent for Bayer, which
yesterday announced short-time working at some of its plants. The shares
fell respectively DM2.60, DM2.40 and DM1.20 to DM227.00, DM254.40 and
DM272.30.
PARIS was firm in early trading, weakened later before sprinting to a gain
in the CAC-40 index of 8.37 to 1,995.12, for a week's rise of 2.6 per cent.
Turnover remained firm at FFr3.8bn.
Speculation on possible stake building continued to lift volume in Suez,
which saw 1.6m shares change hands as the shares gained FFr13.20 to
FFr318.20. Of all the names rumoured to be interested in the group,
including that of Sir James Goldsmith, only UAP, which currently has a 6.5
per cent stake, denied interest. UAP finished FFr11 stronger at FFr586.
The car sector finished a dreadful week with further losses in Peugeot, down
FFr18 at FFr572, Michelin, off FFr4.60 at FFr175.10 and Valeo FFr34 lower at
FFr751.
AMSTERDAM ended a difficult week higher, with the CBS Tendency index up 0.8
at 101.8, up 1.9 per cent on the week. There was lingering interest in
companies which had reported this week with Philips and DSM both 30 cents
higher at Fl 22.80 and Fl 73.50 and Polygram up 50 cents at Fl 49.40.
Heineken set a new record high, up Fl 8.30 or Fl 195.80, but some analysts
felt that the shares were now beginning to look expensive.
MILAN marked time although the market was alive with rumours which made for
an active day's trading. The Comit index eased 1.25 to 535.47 - 4.3 per cent
ahead on the week.
Olivetti fixed L63 or 2.6 per cent lower at L2,385 before easing to L2,365
after hours and Sip was L26 lower at L1,680 amid fears that the groups might
be planning rights issues.
Stet shed L35 to L2,355 before easing to L2,340 after hours on speculation
that it might soon conclude the sale of a stake in its telecommunications
equipment subsidiary Italtel.
In the other direction, Rinascente, L480 or 5.5 per cent ahead at L9,190,
was in demand, particularly by US investors in spite of Fiat's fresh denials
that its sale was being negotiated.
Pirelli broke through the L1,500 level, adding L50 to L1,531 in heavy
volume.
Stocks from the Ligresti group were caught up in speculation about possible
divestments. Holding company Premafin shot up L621 or 12.8 per cent to
L5,450 and were up to L5,650 after hours, while Grassetto, the construction
group, rose L660 or 12.2 per cent to fix at L6,060 before continuing up to
L6,175 after hours.
Elsewhere, the Consob market regulatory agency suspended the shares of
holding company Fimpar and its hotel group Ciga pending an announcement on
the status of Ciga's financial restructuring plan.
ZURICH finished easier but a strengthening dollar enabled shares to pull up
from the day's lows. The SMI index dipped 4.9 to 2,134.6, a 1.6 per cent
rise on the week.
CS Holding fell SFr30 to SFr2,230 after its main asset, Credit Suisse,
reported a 1.1 per cent rise in 1992 group net profit which was at the lower
end of expectations. UBS, which last week reported a 10.4 per cent rise in
net income, rose SFr2 to SFr944.
BBC Brown Boveri shed SFr50 to SFr3,940. Analysts expect the Zurich-based
Asea Brown Boveri, from which BBC derives virtually all its income, to
announce 1992 profit at or below the previous year's level.
STOCKHOLM drew strength from lower debt market yields and better than
expected earnings from Sandvik. The Affarsvarlden Index rose 16.7 to 1,031.2
, a 3.1 per cent rise on the week.
Sandvik's B shares rose SKr12 to SKr465 as the company unexpectedly raised
its dividend and a fall in profits proved not as bad as feared.
