<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON's enthusiastic reception for the easing in repurchase rates in
Germany was fully reflected in the derivates markets yesterday, writes Terry
Byland. The March contract on the FT-SE Index continued to show its strong
premium against the cash market. Trading volume was reduced somewhat, but
the market stood up well to a bout of selling by one source.
News of the Bundesbank's move came soon after the opening of the stock index
future, and the March contract quickly soared to a day's high of 2,938,
holding a 13 point premium against the underlying Footsie. The seller then
drove the contract all the way down to 2,908 but the 2,900 mark was safely
held. The final official quotation of 2,931 showed the contract at a premium
of around 9 points to cash, with the fair value calculation at a four point
discount.
Dealers reported renewed activity on the spread now showing between March
and the June contract. Of total volume of around 8,400 contracts some 1,500
deals reflected intra-contract spread trading.
</TEXT>
