<DATE>930306
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture (Week in the Markets): Price
fall angers platinum producers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE WAS good news and bad news for producers of platinum group metals this
week. After Allied-Signal of the US announced on Tuesday that it had
developed a new palladium-only catalyst for cleaning car exhaust fumes the
price of that metal rose by more than 5 per cent. The trouble was that the
announcement raised the spectre of platinum's displacement from its biggest
single market, and its price fell by 1.75 per cent.
For the South African producers that account for more than half the world's
production of the two metals the palladium price rise would net an extra
Dollars 6m in a full year, while the platinum fall would cost them nearly
Dollars 16m. So they were far from pleased. And any relief they might have
felt when Allied-Signal backtracked on Wednesday, saying the new catalyst
would not replace platinum or rhodium based systems, was overcome by fury at
what they saw as another example of market manipulation.
'Is this fair play?' was the heading of a statement issued on Thursday by Mr
Michael McMahon, chairman of Impala Platinum, the second largest producer of
the metals. He complained of a series of incidents over the past few years
that had hit his company's earnings and in which he detected 'a common
thread'.
Initially, he said, there was overstatement of a position, 'causing severe
downward pressure on the PGM markets'. And these were quickly followed by 'a
retraction, withdrawal, or considerable watering down of the original
message'. That view was backed by Rustenburg Platinum, also of South Africa,
the biggest producer, which warned that continuing depressed prices might
force it to close down loss-making shafts.
While the London palladium price held on to most of its gains - yesterday's
fixing was Dollars 104.75 a troy ounce, up Dollars 4.60 on the week -
platinum made good most of its fall with a Dollars 3.55 rise yesterday to
Dollars 344.30 an ounce, down 70 cents on balance. But that was still
Dollars 25 down from three weeks ago, following an earlier fall that was
blamed by Mr Todd Bruce of Rustplats on claims 'for which there was no
factual support' that Japanese car makers were selling from their own stocks
of the metals.
At the London Metal Exchange it was one-way traffic again, with all base
metals contracts finishing lower on the week.
The sharpest decline was in copper, the cash price for which closed
yesterday at Pounds 1,474.50 a tonne, down Pounds 40 on the week. The
writing was on the wall on Monday when the three months copper price was
pushed through a support area around Dollars 2,150 a tonne to a fresh 3 1/2
 month low.
The main problem for the copper market is the disappearance of the bullish
factors that had been propping it up in January and February - initially
sustained Chinese buying and then floods in Arizona and strikes in Mexico -
while hopes of recovery in the US are being countered by concern about
European and Japanese car production prospects.
The mood of the market has been further undermined this week by an ominous
increase in arrivals from Russia, the source of the floods of aluminium and
nickel that have knocked the stuffing out of those markets. This 'could
prove the last straw for copper,' commented GNI, the London trading house,
in its daily market review yesterday.
The long shadow of the former Soviet Union also extended over the tin market
this week as merchants reported that the Commonwealth of Independent States
was also offering supplies of that metal, and at discount prices.
The gloom was lifted somewhat by yesterday's announcement of a modest
downturn in LME warehouse stocks of tin and the cash price closed at Dollars
5,670 a tonne, down Dollars 100 on the week but Dollars 25 above Wednesday's
low.
At the London Futures and Options Exchange traders were keeping an eye on
the International Cocoa Agreement negotiations in Geneva, though few held
out more than the faintest hope of a positive conclusion.
In the event the past fortnight's round of talks, regarded as a last ditch
attempt to clear the way for a pact with price-stabilisation clauses, was
effectively abandoned on Thursday with producer and consumer delegates still
far apart on the price range to be defended by a stock withholding scheme
and who should pay to finance the scheme.
It was decided, however, to adjourn, rather than to conclude, the meeting as
signs were discerned that some producing countries might be willing to make
big concessions on these questions.
That optimistic view did not seem to have filtered through to the London
market, however, where the May delivery position closed yesterday at Pounds
708 a tonne, down Pounds 41 on the week.
In the oil market the bullish implications of last month's agreement by
members of the Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries to cut
production have been failing to dispel fears of continuing excess supply,
but prices managed to break out of the recent narrow trading ranges this
week as good refiner buying of crude was seen in Europe and signs emerged of
Indian demand.
The May delivery price at London's International Petroleum Exchange was
trading at Dollars 19.48 a barrel late yesterday up 54 cents on the week.
