<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Cookson to raise Pounds 185.6m via rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES IN Cookson Group fell by 14p to 199p yesterday, after the industrial
materials company confirmed that it is raising Pounds 185.6m through a
1-for-4 rights issue priced at 170p.
The proceeds of the rights, which has been underwritten by Lazard Brothers,
will be used to repay debt, fund organic growth and make complementary
acquisitions.
Cookson raised Pounds 83m through a rights issue two years, after an
acquisitions spree in the late-1980s left it heavily burdened with debt.
Since then a new management team has undertaken a substantial restructuring
of the group, making selective disposals and refocusing it on four product
divisions.
The company also reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 72.5m for the year to
end-December, against a deficit of Pounds 7.9m last time. The comparisons
have been restated to conform with accounting rule FRS 3.
The 1991 figure was originally reported as a profit of Pounds 34.4m.
However, FRS 3 required the restatement of extraordinary items in 1991 to
include goodwill previously written off to reserves on sale or termination
of operations, and for these extraordinary items to be reclassified as
exceptional items.
Turnover declined by 5 per cent to Pounds 1.24bn (Pounds 1.3bn). However,
like-for-like turnover, adjusting for acquisitions, disposals and exchange
rate movements, increased by about 3 per cent.
Earnings per share were 9.4p against restated losses per share of 8.4p in
1991. Last year it reported earnings of 1.8p.
An unchanged final dividend of 3p is proposed, maintaining the total for the
year at 6p.
Operating profit before exceptional items increased to Pounds 94.5m, an
increase of 26 per cent over a restated Pounds 74.6m in 1991.
About 80 per cent of the group's business is outside the UK and the effect
of currency translation was to add Pounds 7.5m to sales last year and Pounds
1.1m to pre-tax profits.
All four divisions achieved increased operating profits after exceptional
items. The electronic materials division showed a 66 per cent increase to
Pounds 21.4m (Pounds 12.9m), while the ceramics division posted increased
operating profits of Pounds 38.5m (Pounds 31.4m). The engineering products
division turned in an Pounds 8.8m advance to Pounds 13.8m, boosted by the
acquisition in April last year of the remaining 50 per cent of Stern Leach.
The plastics division posted operating profits of Pounds 14.2m (Pounds
9.5m).
At the end of December the group had net borrowings of Pounds 341m,
including Pounds 77m of convertible preference shares, an increase of Pounds
125m from the end of 1991. The main reasons for the increase were Pounds 55m
of additional borrowings arising from the acquisition of the remaining 50
per cent stake in Stern Leach following the exercise of a put option by the
former joint venture partner, a Pounds 31m foreign currency translation
adjustment, and an increase in year-end working capital.
Gearing, which increased from 51 per cent at the end of 1991 to 74 per cent
at the end of 1992, will be reduced to below 30 per cent as a result of the
rights issue.
See Lex
</TEXT>
