<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Go-ahead for Pounds 200m Manchester retail plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, CHRIS TIGHE and NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 200m scheme for one of the largest out-of-town shopping centres in
the UK yesterday won planning permission from Mr Michael Howard, environment
secretary.
The 300-acre Trafford Centre at Dumplington near Manchester, which will have
1m sq ft of shopping and sports facilities, will be the largest retail
project in the north-west of England.
The decision was greeted with dismay by local authorities, developers and
retailers who fear it will further increase already fierce competition, to
the detriment of the many shopping centres in the greater Manchester area.
Work on the centre is expected to begin within two years and is likely to be
completed by 1997.
Property experts said it was likely that the centre would be the last large
shopping centre to win planning approval.
Very few property schemes have been initiated since the property market went
into decline three years ago but Mr Robert Hough, chairman of Manchester
Ship Canal Company, the developers of the site, is confident of attracting
finance and tenants. He said: 'It is a greenfield site, linked to three
motorways with a large conurbation on its doorstep. It will be a magnet into
the north-west.'
More than 7m people live within an hour's drive of the site which is bounded
by Trafford Park, the M63 and the Manchester Ship Canal.
Critics of the scheme said the decision appeared to cut across draft
planning guidelines issued by the government at the end of last year. These
favoured planning restraint for out-of-town shopping centres to protect
existing centres.
A consortium of eight of greater Manchester's 10 metropolitan district
councils and five large property developers, which oppose the proposal, is
considering whether to mount a High Court challenge.
Mr David Kaiserman, senior assistant city planning officer for Manchester
City Council, said: 'We see development of this type making it even more
difficult to achieve regeneration in the inner parts of the city. A large
peripheral development appealing only to people who have cars is not doing
anything at all in our view in net terms for urban regeneration.'
Mr David Brown, president of the Manchester Chamber of Trade and manager of
the city's Arndale Centre, said: 'Something like this will have an effect on
all levels of trade in the city of Manchester and other surrounding towns
and will inevitably lead to job losses in the city centre. It will affect
the big multiples and the small guys.'
Mr Brown said there was already a 'massive choice' of retail outlets in
Manchester and the 10 large towns in an outlying 10-mile radius.
The consortium opposed to the scheme includes P&amp;O, owners of Manchester's
Arndale Centre, MEPC, Land Securities, Norwich Union and Shudehill, a
company formed by the Co-operative Insurance Society and the Co-operative
Wholesale Society.
Shudehill has planning permission for a 500,000 sq ft retail development on
a site beside the Arndale Centre. Mr Kaiserman said Shudehill had indicated
it would have to reconsider its plan.
Trafford Metropolitan Borough Council, which covers Dumplington, welcomed
the decision to give the go-ahead for the centre.
Mr Michael Crawley, senior assistant director for plan-ning, said it would
contribute to regeneration at Trafford Park and complement rather than
adversely affect other centres.
</TEXT>
