<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Smith calls for Leyland Daf help
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, yesterday challenged Mr John Major, the
prime minister, to demonstrate his commitment to Britain's manufacturing
sector by ensuring a future for Leyland Daf.
He contrasted the moves by the Dutch government to preserve as much as
possible of the company's plants in the Netherlands with the insistence of
British ministers that the receiver should be left to decide what could be
salvaged.
Mr Smith told the north-west regional conference of the Labour party in
Blackpool that the Dutch government had been willing to invest in the
company because it recognised the value to the economy of its technology and
the skills of its workforce. Dutch workers knew their plants were secure,
while British workers still did not know what would become of them, he said.
A planned demonstration tomorrow to protest against alleged government
refusal to help Leyland Daf was understood to have been called off last
night after being attacked as 'ill-conceived' and a 'cheap trick' by the
Leyland Daf dealers' association.
Both the administrative receivers of Leyland Daf, and management teams
staging separate buy-out attempts for the vans operation in Birmingham and
truck plant at Leyland, Lancashire, are understood to have been dismayed and
irritated by the planned protest and a poster campaign which sprang up
yesterday throughout the UK.
</TEXT>
