<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAR 93 / Tougher investor protection urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SELF-REGULATION of the financial services industry has failed the consumer
and should be replaced by a statutory Office of Investor Protection, the
Consumers' Association said yesterday.
The group, in a review of the six-year-old Financial Services Act, said the
present system was 'far too deeply flawed' to be remedied easily and the
entire act should be scrapped.
While acknowledging that the act had made some improvements in protecting
investors, particularly in the provision of a compensation scheme for those
who suffered losses, it said there were far more shortcomings.
The association, a voluntary organisation with more than 800,000 members,
said: 'There is considerable evidence that the regulatory system has
delivered inadequate standards of monitoring and enforcement, resulting in
unacceptably high levels of fraud and widespread mis-selling.'
The association estimated that the annual loss to consumers in the first
year of contracts being signed was about Pounds 250m. Charges are deducted
in the first few years of a policy's life. As a result those who surrender
early lose most or all of their premium payments.
The association said the Financial Services Act, which allows many
businesses to choose between several self-regulatory bodies, had created
'regulatory arbitrage', allowing large integrated groups to shop around for
the most sympathetic regulator.
In citing evidence of widespread mis-selling, the association noted that
during the 1988-89 tax year, personal pensions were sold to 63,000 women
with no earnings who did not even qualify for such plans.
The association recommended that a regulator be established similar to those
overseeing public utilities.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P60   Depository Institutions.
    P61   Nondepository Institutions.
    P62   Security and Commodity Brokers.
    P63   Insurance Carriers.
    P64   Insurance Agents, Brokers, and Service.
    P67   Holding and Other Investment Offices.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Standards.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
